attributes.name: Welcome To Karta
attributes.text:
Pan the canvas with middle-mouse dragging or a touchpad. Zoom with the mouse wheel or by pinching.

To learn how to use this app, look down to see the node called "Guide - Hub", then right click and select "Enter Context" to be taken to the guide.

Feedback and thoughts are greatly appreciated! See the top left menu for contact details.

attributes.name: Guide - Data and View
attributes.text:
The most important thing to know about nodes is that the contents and the presentation of them are separate.

The content of each node is unique, but they can have many different Instances.

This gives you the freedom to reuse nodes in different contexts, and navigate between them through the associations you create yourself.

attributes.name: Guide - Edges Explicitly Connect
attributes.text:
The lines between nodes are called Edges. They exist in the content layer, so they are Context-independent.

They are used to connect nodes together in a more explicit way. Use edges to say "these nodes belong together".

attributes.name: Guide - Relativity Intro
attributes.text:
Here's the fun part:

Node instances can have different sizes and colors depending on the context they're in. It's all relative.

Try this out. In this context there's a node called "Guide - Relativity". Enter it's context to see what we're talking about.

attributes.name: Guide - End
attributes.text:
That's the end of the guide!

Here, the root node. Move to its Context to begin your own web of ideas.

attributes.name: Guide - Native Version
attributes.text:
The full vision of Karta is to act as a file browser. 

Karta would then be a native application you could download, with access to some section of a user's folders and files.

Same features as here in the web version (and the usual file browsing features), but with the ability to navigate contexts of any folder or file and connect any of them to any other.

attributes.name: Guide - Exporting Standalone Apps
attributes.text:
It would be cool to be able to export these networks as standalone read-only applications you could host on a website. At least I want to do it for my own website.

However, to do this, and to allow others to use these exports however they wish, even commercially, the licensing needs to be tackled.

attributes.name: Guide - Creating Nodes Heading
attributes.text: Creating Nodes

attributes.name: Guide - Context Fundamentals
attributes.text:
In Karta, we're always looking at the network from the point of view of some node. This point of view is called that node's Context. That node is called that context's Focal Node. You can tell what the focal is based on the thick bright outline it has. 

Any node can have a context that you can enter, and that context can contain any other nodes. Nodes that appear in multiple contexts are referencing the same underlying node, which means that we don't have to duplicate nodes to put them in multiple places.

attributes.name: Guide - Motivation for Karta
attributes.text:
Karta's purpose is to help with managing complex creative projects.

Worldbuilding, moodboards, concept organisation, inter-project connections, real world references, and so on. It fills a need that wasn't quite fulfilled with existing tools, however mature they may be.

File systems are rigid and awkward to explore. You can only go up and down in the hierarchy of folders. Files can't exist in multiple places at the same time.

Whiteboarding apps inherit the limitations of physical whiteboards. One 2D surface per canvas. Siloed and static.

The idea was to put all of one's work in the same place, turning every individual piece into a node. Then one may connect nodes to any others, connecting them by relevance. The end result is an interconnected web of work and ideas that you navigate intuitively along lines of association, where each view transitions smoothly to the next. Nodes are unique but can be used in many ways, so there's no duplication, and no enforced hierarchy.

While a decent start, there's a couple other steps until this app meets these needs properly. To read more on those, head over to the roadmap.

attributes.name: Guide - Karta Feedback
attributes.text:
Thanks for taking the tour!

This app is an MVP, a minimal viable product. It's the least that could be done to showcase the idea, be fun to play with, and in some cases even useful.

There's plenty of things to add and improve from this point. If you have ideas, suggestions or general feedback, do please send them by email. 

karta@teodosin.com

I will be posting updates, mostly on Bluesky. Follow me there @teodosin.bsky.social. 

For future plans, proceed to the roadmap. If you're interested in the "why" of this app, pan down to read the motivations.

attributes.name: Guide - View Navigation
attributes.text:
To navigate within a context:

* Panning - drag with middle-mouse pressed, or two-finger drag with a touchpad.

* Zooming - use scroll wheel, or two-finger pinch with a touchpad. 

* Center the focal node - from the background's right-click menu, or by pressing "F"

* Frame the current view contents - from the background's right-click menu, or by pressing Shift + "F"

attributes.name: Guide - Roadmap Intro
attributes.text:
In addition the standard quality-of-life improvements and bug fixes, there are a few larger steps that will be taken next. 

These are near-term and quite likely to happen, despite other obligations.

And of course, if there's interest from users, we can dream bigger. But let's stay here for now.

attributes.name: Guide - Deleting Edges
attributes.text:
To delete edges, select one or more edges and right-click to find the option to delete them.

Multi-select with Shift pressed, because box select doesn't select edges yet.

Bear in mind that deleting an edge will delete it permanently from all Contexts. Adding it back adds it back to all of them too, though. And the nodes added to Contexts in this way will remain there. So deleting edges is less dangerous than deleting nodes.

attributes.name: Guide - Moving and Scaling Nodes
attributes.text:
Move nodes with the Move tool selected on the Tool bar to the left. 

Drag a node to move it. 

Drag on the background to box select multiple nodes. 

Hold shift to add or remove from the current selection. 

Drag on the handles in the corners of your selection to resize.

attributes.name: Guide - Navigating Between Contexts
attributes.text:
Navigating between contexts:

Right-click on a node and press "Enter Context" to see the node network from that node's point of view.

You can also use the Context Tool from the Tool Bar on the left of the screen to make all node clicks change between contexts.

attributes.name: Guide - Node Properties
attributes.text:
On the top right of the screen by default, you'll find the Properties Panel. 

By default it is collapsed, but you can expand it by clicking the icon on the right side of it.

Turning off the Pin will make the Panel invisible when no nodes or multiple nodes are selected.

From the Panel you can edit a node's Attributes. Its name, whether its name label is visible, and if its a text node, its color and font settings. Try it! Edit any of the nodes that exist in the Guide.

attributes.name: Guide - Creating Nodes
attributes.text:
To create a new node, right-click on the background and select "Create Node Here". You will be prompted to select from a few types of nodes. You can also press Tab to directly open this list.

Images created this way will be just empty frames. To actually add an image to a Context, paste a copied image or drag a file into the window. 

Text nodes will be empty at first. All the headings and text paragraphs you've seen so far are just Text nodes. That should give you an idea of what you can do with them.

A basic Node is just a filled rounded rectangle. Use them when you don't need any other features, just a point in conceptual space and a name for it.

You can also bring nodes into a Context by searching for them. Right-click on the background to find the search function. Any existing node can be found there.

attributes.name: Guide - What Edges Do
attributes.text:
Two nodes connected by an edge are always present in each other's Contexts. Even if you remove one from the other's Context, it will appear there again when you leave and come back.

This is true for any number of connections, and is a convenient way to carry nodes to other contexts. Connect a bunch of nodes to another, enter the latter's context, and all those nodes will be there.

attributes.name: Guide - Move to Topics
attributes.text: To the right are the topics of this guide. Move to any of their contexts to learn more about their respective topics.

attributes.text: Moving and Scaling Nodes

attributes.name: Guide - Karta in a Nutshell
attributes.text:
Karta can be thought of as a note-taking tool, similar to many canvases you may be familiar with.

In Karta, every text note and image is a node in a network. They're not tied to any particular location or canvas, but can be referenced anywhere. No information gets duplicated. Since they can appear in many places, we can navigate our collection of nodes intuitively through the associations and connections they make.

attributes.name: Guide - Creating Edges
attributes.text:
You can create edges by selecting one or more nodes and dragging from the red circle on the bottom of the selection. End the drag on a node to connect all selected nodes to that one. 

Try it! Connect this node to another one in this context.

attributes.text: Removing and Deleting Nodes

attributes.name: Guide - More on Contexts
attributes.text:
Nodes don't have contexts by default. You can tell which nodes have contexts based on the dim outline that they have.

When you enter the context of a node that doesn't yet have one, it is automatically created. The previous focal node will be added so you can get back easily.

You can also navigation buttons on the bottom left to go back, forward, or choose any existing context to go to.

attributes.name: Guide - Open Source
attributes.text:
The old parts of Karta are already open-source under the GPL-3 license. The intention is not to ask for money for anyone to just download and use the app. The editor and its forks should remain free, hence the choice of license.

For exports though, the GPL-3 license is too restrictive. If you make and publish a network for Karta, you should be able to use it commercially. So some thinking is needed to separate out the necessary runtime and license it more liberally than the editor.

I don't want to rush this process. If Karta is useful to people other than me, it'll be worth it to do this well and set up the app for long-term progress. 

Get in touch if you have thoughts :)

attributes.name: Guide - Nodes Heading
attributes.text: Nodes

attributes.name: Guide - Removing and Deleting Nodes
attributes.text:
There are two ways to get rid of a node. These correspond to the data and instance separation.

To simply remove a node from just the current context, right-click on a node and select "Remove from Context". This will remove that node from the current context, but it will still remain in other contexts, and you can still bring it back by searching for it.

The other, more permanent solution is to Delete Permanently. This will remove the core data of a node. It will not be searchable anymore and any instances that reference it in other contexts will simply show a ghost. This will also delete that node's Context if it exists. 

Be careful. Karta doesn't yet have undo-redo!
